04817nam a22006615i 9780822388197DE-B159720201125033335.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||201125t20062006ncu    fo  d z      eng d  a97808223881977 a10.1515/97808223881972doi  a(DE-B1597)552212  a(OCoLC)262341485  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  ancucUS-NC 4aRM263b.D44 2006 7aMED0710002bisacsh04a615/.11 aDeGrandpre, Richard, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut14aThe Cult of Pharmacology :bHow America Became the World's Most Troubled Drug Culture /cRichard DeGrandpre. 1aDurham : bDuke University Press, c[2006] 4cÂ©2006  a1 online resource (312 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tPreface -- tPart One End of a Century -- t1 Mama coca -- t2 Cult of the ssri -- t3 The emperor's new smokes -- tPart Two Earlier Times -- t4 The placebo text -- t5 America's domestic drug affair -- t6 War -- tPart Three While at War -- t7 The drug reward -- t8 Possessed by the stimulus -- t9 Ideology -- tAppendix One escalation of american drug laws in the twentieth century -- tAppendix Two u.s. regulations allowing a white market for drugs in the twentieth century -- tNotes -- tSelective Bibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aAmerica had a radically different relationship with drugs a century ago. Drug prohibitions were few, and while alcohol was considered a menace, the public regularly consumed substances that are widely demonized today. Heroin was marketed by Bayer Pharmaceuticals, and marijuana was available as a tincture of cannabis sold by Parke Davis and Company.Exploring how this rather benign relationship with psychoactive drugs was transformed into one of confusion and chaos, The Cult of Pharmacology tells the dramatic story of how, as one legal drug after another fell from grace, new pharmaceutical substances took their place. Whether Valium or OxyContin at the pharmacy, cocaine or meth purchased on the street, or alcohol and tobacco from the corner store, drugs and drug use proliferated in twentieth-century America despite an escalating war on "drugs."Richard DeGrandpre, a past fellow of the National Institute on Drug Abuse and author of the best-selling book Ritalin Nation, delivers a remarkably original interpretation of drugs by examining the seductive but ill-fated belief that they are chemically predestined to be either good or evil. He argues that the determination to treat the medically sanctioned use of drugs such as Miltown or Seconal separately from the illicit use of substances like heroin or ecstasy has blinded America to how drugs are transformed by the manner in which a culture deals with them.Bringing forth a wealth of scientific research showing the powerful influence of social and psychological factors on how the brain is affected by drugs, DeGrandpre demonstrates that psychoactive substances are not angels or demons irrespective of why, how, or by whom they are used. The Cult of Pharmacology is a bold and necessary new account of America's complex relationship with drugs.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 25. Nov 2020) 0aDrug utilizationzUnited States. 0aDrugsxSocial aspectszUnited States. 0aPharmaceutical industryzUnited States. 4aLSD. 4aRitalin. 4acocaine. 4adrug policy and drug use. 4aopiates. 4apsychoactive drugs. 4apsyschopharmacology. 4asubstance abuse. 4awar on drugs. 7aMEDICAL / Pharmacology.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDUK Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013z978311071183740uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9780822388197zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780822388197423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cov